    _ipc_doc(section='268', title='Public Nuisance', focus='Section 268 defines public nuisance as an act or illegal omission causing common injury, danger, or annoyance to the public or people in general who dwell or occupy property in the vicinity, or which necessarily causes injury, obstruction, danger, or annoyance to persons using public rights.', punishment='Being a definitional provision, punishment normally comes from allied sections such as Section 290 IPC for punishment of public nuisance or special local statutes dealing with obstruction, pollution, noise, and unsafe activities.', related='Sections 290 and 291 IPC, municipal laws, environmental statutes, police powers relating to public ways, and tort principles on nuisance', case_law='Courts distinguish public nuisance from a purely private wrong. The focus is on effect upon the public or a considerable class of persons rather than a single individual grievance.', procedure='complaints often arise from obstruction of roads, loud activities, hazardous emissions, encroachment, unsafe structures, or recurring neighbourhood conduct affecting public convenience'),
    _ipc_doc(section='279', title='Rash Driving or Riding on a Public Way', focus='Section 279 penalises rash or negligent driving on a public way in a manner likely to endanger human life or likely to cause hurt or injury. It is frequently invoked in road accident prosecutions alongside causing hurt or death by negligence.', punishment='The section provides imprisonment, fine, or both, and often accompanies Sections 337, 338, or 304A IPC depending on the actual result caused by the driving. Motor Vehicles Act consequences may also follow.', related='Sections 279, 337, 338, 304A IPC, the Motor Vehicles Act, site inspection evidence, mechanical inspection reports, and drunken-driving rules where applicable', case_law='Courts assess speed, lane discipline, visibility, braking marks, traffic conditions, and witness testimony; mere high speed is not always enough unless rashness or negligence is specifically proved.', procedure='the case usually depends on spot panchnama, mechanical inspection, CCTV, eyewitnesses, post-accident conduct, and expert reconstruction of how the vehicle was handled'),
    _ipc_doc(section='302', title='Punishment for Murder', focus='The section belongs to the IPC framework governing homicide, death-causing conduct, or attempts against life. Courts closely analyse intention, knowledge, causation, medical opinion, the nature of the weapon, body part targeted, motive, and whether any statutory exception applies.', punishment='Punishment in this chapter ranges from fine or limited imprisonment in negligence cases to life imprisonment or death in murder cases. Attempt offences and dowry death carry severe custodial sentences even where death has not been intentionally completed by a straightforward act.', related='Sections 299 to 304B IPC, Sections 306 to 309 IPC, Section 113A and 113B of the Evidence Act, Sections 174 and 176 CrPC, inquest law, dying declarations, and post-mortem jurisprudence', case_law='Leading interpretation comes from Virsa Singh, K.M. Nanavati, Bachan Singh, Machhi Singh, and many later cases distinguishing murder from culpable homicide not amounting to murder, and intention from mere knowledge or rashness.', procedure='cases generally involve immediate FIR, seizure of weapon, forensic examination, post-mortem report, motive evidence, recovery evidence, dying declaration if available, and trial scrutiny of whether the proved mental element matches the exact charge framed'),
