    _ipc_doc(section='309', title='Attempt to Commit Suicide', focus='Section 309 historically criminalised an attempt to commit suicide. Its formal text remains in the IPC, but mental-health based reform has drastically reduced its practical use.', punishment='The Mental Healthcare Act, 2017 creates a presumption of severe stress and directs the State to provide care, treatment, and rehabilitation rather than routine prosecution. The Ministry of Home Affairs also advised effective decriminalised handling in practice.', related='Section 309 IPC, the Mental Healthcare Act 2017, police and hospital response protocols, and constitutional discussions on dignity and autonomy', case_law='Modern decisions and policy guidance emphasise treatment, counselling, and crisis intervention. Courts now treat prosecution as exceptional and inconsistent with a rights-based mental health framework.', procedure='police generally secure medical treatment first, inform family, document circumstances, and avoid a punitive response unless some distinct criminal angle or fabricated incident is involved'),
    _ipc_doc(section='319', title='Hurt', focus='These provisions define hurt and grievous hurt, classify the seriousness of bodily injury, and punish voluntary infliction of such harm. Medical evidence, x-rays, disability, duration of pain, and the weapon used are frequently decisive.', punishment='The penalty becomes progressively harsher as the injury shifts from simple hurt to grievous hurt, and further when dangerous weapons, corrosives, or acid are used. Some sections are definitional, while others prescribe imprisonment and fine.', related='Sections 319 to 326B IPC, Sections 34 and 149 IPC for joint liability, medical jurisprudence on fracture and permanent privation, and compensation principles under criminal procedure', case_law='Courts often examine whether the injury actually falls within the eight categories of grievous hurt, whether fracture is proved, and whether the accused intended the resulting injury or merely participated in a sudden fight.', procedure='the prosecution ordinarily relies on wound certificates, x-rays, treating doctor testimony, seizure of weapons, photographs, forensic reports, and witness evidence showing the manner of assault and the body part targeted'),
    _ipc_doc(section='320', title='Grievous Hurt', focus='These provisions define hurt and grievous hurt, classify the seriousness of bodily injury, and punish voluntary infliction of such harm. Medical evidence, x-rays, disability, duration of pain, and the weapon used are frequently decisive.', punishment='The penalty becomes progressively harsher as the injury shifts from simple hurt to grievous hurt, and further when dangerous weapons, corrosives, or acid are used. Some sections are definitional, while others prescribe imprisonment and fine.', related='Sections 319 to 326B IPC, Sections 34 and 149 IPC for joint liability, medical jurisprudence on fracture and permanent privation, and compensation principles under criminal procedure', case_law='Courts often examine whether the injury actually falls within the eight categories of grievous hurt, whether fracture is proved, and whether the accused intended the resulting injury or merely participated in a sudden fight.', procedure='the prosecution ordinarily relies on wound certificates, x-rays, treating doctor testimony, seizure of weapons, photographs, forensic reports, and witness evidence showing the manner of assault and the body part targeted'),
