    _ipc_doc(section='354', title='Assault or Criminal Force to Woman with Intent to Outrage Her Modesty', focus='These offences protect bodily integrity, sexual autonomy, privacy, dignity, and freedom of movement of women. The statutory text has been strengthened through criminal law amendments after 2013 and is interpreted in a victim-sensitive manner.', punishment='Punishment varies widely: from relatively shorter terms for verbal or non-contact harassment to long imprisonment for rape, trafficking, and aggravated sexual offences. Some provisions are definitional and operate with allied punishment sections.', related='Sections 354 to 376 IPC, Section 509 IPC, the Evidence Act provisions on sexual offence testimony, the POCSO Act for child victims, medical examination rules, and victim compensation schemes', case_law='Key decisions stress consent, absence of stereotypes, dignity of survivors, hostile environment evidence, digital proof in stalking or voyeurism matters, and the need to avoid character assassination in cross-examination.', procedure="police must promptly register FIR in cognizable sexual offences, arrange medical examination, record the survivor's statement carefully, preserve electronic evidence, consider Section 164 CrPC statements, and support witness protection and compensation processes"),
