    _ipc_doc(section='377', title='Unnatural Offences', focus='Section 377 originally penalised carnal intercourse against the order of nature. After Navtej Singh Johar, consensual sexual relations between adults in private are no longer criminal under this section.', punishment='The provision survives only for non-consensual acts, acts involving minors, and bestiality. Punishment for those surviving categories remains serious and can extend to life imprisonment depending on the facts and statutory wording.', related='Navtej Singh Johar, sexual offence law, POCSO for child victims, rape and assault provisions, consent principles, and constitutional rights to dignity and privacy', case_law='The modern constitutional position is that morality cannot criminalise consensual adult intimacy. Investigators must therefore focus on lack of consent, age, coercion, or animal involvement rather than sexual orientation.', procedure='charging practice now treats the section as a narrow residual offence and not a tool to target consensual adult same-sex relations'),
    _ipc_doc(section='378', title='Theft', focus='This group criminalises dishonest taking, extortionary pressure, robbery, dacoity, misappropriation, breach of trust, cheating, fraudulent dealings with property, mischief, trespass, and forgery. The unifying element is dishonest intention or deliberate interference with property or legal rights.', punishment='Punishments escalate with violence, breach of trust by fiduciaries, forged valuable securities, night-time house-breaking, armed robbery, dacoity, and counterfeit currency. Some sections define the offence while allied sections prescribe the sentence.', related='Sections 378 to 471 IPC, Sections 489A to 489E IPC, Section 34 and 120B IPC, the Evidence Act on documentary proof, handwriting or forensic opinion, and recovery provisions under the CrPC', case_law='Courts look for dishonest intention at inception, entrustment in breach-of-trust cases, deception causing delivery in cheating matters, actual or threatened violence in robbery, and falsity or intention to cheat in forgery prosecutions.', procedure='investigation commonly centres on ownership records, seizure memos, recovery from possession, bank or transaction trails, handwriting comparison, valuation evidence, CCTV footage, and witness proof of possession, threat, delivery, or trespass'),
